g.text: Understanding how SARS-CoV-2, thevirus that causes COVID-19, spreadscan help you protect yourself and thepeople around you.

text.tspan: When you breathe, talk, laugh, shout,
sing – really any time air leaves your
mouth or nose - your body produces
respiratory droplets. These droplets are
produced all the time and can carry all
kinds of things, including SARS-CoV-2,
the virus that causes COVID-19

g.text: Remember, you and those around youcould be spreading COVID-19 beforesymptoms appear!

text.tspan: The droplets fly through the air, sometimes traveling more than
12 ft! These droplets can land in eyes, mouths, and noses and
be breathed in by those around you, spreading COVID-19.

g.text: So when you're in a place where you can't consistently keepyour distance, it's more likely that droplets that are producedend up infecting you or those around you.

text.tspan: The droplets can also land on
surfaces that others may touch. Then
COVID-19 spreads when those people
touch their eyes, nose, or mouth.
For a COVID-19 infection to take
hold, an individual needs to be
exposed to
a certain amount
of
the virus. This is called
an
infectious dose
. Researchers
aren't sure what that dose is yet.
However, the infectious dose is
likely very low.
We should do
everything we can to keep our
exposure to the virus as minimal
as possible.

g.text: Since droplets carry thevirus and are probablythe primary mode of spread, to keep dangerlow, we must reduce ourexposure to droplets.

In addition to keeping your distance from other droplet producers (people), you can reduce your exposure todroplets by keeping activities and interactions short.Anything can happen when you give it enough time. Thesame is true for transmitting or contracting COVID-19.The more time you spend engaged in activity, themore chances you give droplets to reach you and thosearound you.

Lastly, many indoor ventilation systemssimply recycle or recirculate the same airover and over, pushing virus-laden dropletsall over the place! Air filters and openwindows and doors can help to clean anddilute the air.
The best bet is the outdoors where air currents, sunlight, humidity, and other factors help to dissipate droplets produced by others and reducethe infectiousness of those droplets.
